review_blob: Pours hazy yellow, but no sediment in the bottle... Aroma is banana all the way, with some spice.  Banana hits with the flavor as well, but there is a bit of hoppyness that I wasnt expecting, but also cant put my finger on completely.  Good summer beer and the fact that it is organic and (somewhat) local boosts the appeal.

Pours a pale orange, with minimal head...  aroma is faint malt, but nothing really jumps out at you...  flavor is where it gets interesting.  Orange notes, with strong flavor of honey.  I would put this much closer to a dry mead than any sort of beer, but there is the faint aftertaste of hops.  Very interesting.
beer_name: Dogfish Head Midas Touch Golden Elixir

review_blob: Well deserving of high ratings...  it has the oatmeal stout perfection of a sam smith oatmeal stout, with a high quality coffee flavor.  As a coffee lover and a stout lover, this is almost heaven.  Mouthfeel would get over a 5 rating if possible...  the aroma is a little weaker than expected, which is why it got the lowest of the ratings...  Flavor is roasty stout and roasty coffee blending just about perfectly.

11/17/08, tap at the Coxe Ave. location of APBC.  Pours like a standard porter, looks a bit thin.  Flavor is hard roasted malts.  Not a great porter, but palatable.  Would be better if it didnt seem so watery.

On tap at Coxe Ave. location, 11/17/08.  Pours hazy orange, with a fluffy white head.  Bright hop aroma, like it might have been dry hopped or hop backed.  There was enough malt in this one to show through all of the hops.

On tap at Barleys in Asheville, 11/15/08...  dark brown, nice head and minimal lacing.  Roasty aroma and flavor.  This was a fairly sour porter to not be an imperial, etc...  the finish had a nice coffee flavor, and there were bittersweet chocolate notes throughout.  It probably wasnt as smooth and balanced as I was hoping.

On tap at Barleys in Asheville...  This was a nice holiday ale, since it was a bit darker than most, and the spices and sweetness were very subdued.  Pours a dark brown, the aroma is of cinnamon (it has mace in it as well, but who has a nose for that?)--- the spices seem to numb the tongue nicely.

Im not greatly familiar with the "wild" ales, but that being said, I could easily drink this one again.  Pours golden with a rocky head.  Aroma is fruity with a yeasty aroma, but not all that funky.  The funk comes out in the flavor.  Sour and earthy...  Im going to have to go after more of the "funk" beers.
beer_name: De Proefbrouwerij / Allagash Les Deux Brasseurs

review_blob: HST, RIP...  I had this once prior to my rating days, and I remembered thinking it was a bit too sweet... on this go around, it is just about perfect.  Pours opaque brown, with more lacing than head...  aroma is sweet cold coffee.  Thick, rich brew that has flavors of coffee, some chocolate, grapefruity hops, and a nice dry finish.  A big porter to be sure, but is relatively easy to drink.  Being a great beer, dedicated to HST, I have to push this one up to the tops on my list.

Pours jet black with a mottled dark brown head.  The head dissipates quickly leaving a silky smooth beer with a faint ring around the edge of the glass.  Aroma is dominated by roasted malts, but the chocolate is pronounced.  Mouthfeel is extremely smooth and well rounded, but not to the point of being thick.  Dark chocolate and coffee flavors dominate, with alcohol and licorice.  Bitterness seems to come more from the roasted malts than hops, as indicated by the salty hints on the back of the tongue.  This one is good.
beer_name: Stone 20th Anniversary Encore Series: Bitter Chocolate Oatmeal Stout

review_blob: Pours a nice golden, but pretty much zero head.  For me, this one was too sweet and a little one dimensional.  There are a few nice flavors from the funky yeast, but mostly this is a sweet, high alcohol beer.  Something needs to balance out the sweetness.

Pours thin for a porter.  Is much lighter than a typical porter.  The vanilla has a decent aroma, and it does smell like it would be better than it is...  thin, with a bitter/sour note that I doubt is supposed to be there.  I might chalk this one up to a bad bottle, but I doubt Id give it much more of a try.

Pours red with minimal head.  Aroma is malty, with a bit of lager green to it.   Flavor isnt as hoppy as I had hoped for, more malty and Carmel...  overall not a bad beer, but I had this right after the stone Guardian... this one pales in comparison.
beer_name: Flying Dog Horn Dog Barley Wine

review_blob: Hazy orange beer with a minimal head.  Lacing isnt anything to write home about.  Aroma is of grapefruit hops.  Flavor is cascade dominated as well, with the malt supplying a nice caramel note to it.  Palate is almost perfect.  Soft full body, with the right amount of carbonation.  With the hops supplying a dry, bitter end, you wouldnt think this is a 10%+ beer.  Very good.

Had this right after the Flying Dog Double...  this one is much more balanced.  Aroma is hoppy with a caramel background.  A more roasted American strong that balances the subdued sweetness with the kick of the hops.  Bells has some serious competition as my favorite brewery in Great Lakes.

Aroma is sweet hoppy goodness...  pours a hazy orange/amber with minimal head.  Lacing is extreme on this one.  Flavor is hoppy as anything Ive had in a while.  There is a strong bit of sweetness to this one as well.  Its almost like a sweeter version of Stone Arrogant Bastard.  The swallow is dry and bitter.  Excellent display of American hops.
beer_name: Flying Dog Double Dog Double Pale Ale

review_blob: Pours a beautiful copper color, but minimal head.  Aroma is a bit of nutty sweetness.  Flavor is sweet and alcoholic.  Not a lot going on in the flavor for me.  There is a dry woodsy note to it, almost like very watered down whiskey.

Hm...  this one is different than most Ive had.  Ive enjoyed a few krieks, but this doesnt seem as much like that as I expected.  There isnt the bubbly sour tang that a Kriek has.  This is more like a mulled wine.  I guess thats from the fact that it is supposed to be heated.  I drank cold at first, but let it warm.  Aroma is sweet and fruity.  There is more of a cinnamon flavor up front than cherries.  Not sure I would run to this beer, but given what it is, it is a good brew.

This beer isnt rated high enough in my opinion.  I tend to be a bit higher on a lot of beers, but this one isnt as bad as some folks are making it out to be.  Pours a nice amber with a thin beige head.  Aroma is caramel and lightly roasted malt.  There is a bit of hoppiness to this one which is nice in a Marzen.  A bit less sweet than most German Oktoberfests, which is different, but a nice change.

12 oz bottle.  Maybe the most interesting looking bottle Ive seen.  Great theory for the beer, and it works.  Pours a hazy amber with minimal head.  Aroma is earthy and sweet malt.  Mouthfeel is thick and chewy, with a bit of alcohol burn to it.  Flavors are nutty and earthy.  Not as much on the spice as a lot of true Belgians.  No sediment, so this one tastes a bit "cleaner" than a lot of the yeasty abbey style ales.

Great dark lager.  Grassy aroma... pours amber with a fluffy head.  Flavor is crisp and green like a good lager should taste, but with the roasted malts rounding out the flavor.  Bready flavors as well.  Nice body to this one as well.

Pours hazy orange with minimal head.  Aroma is a spiced fruity blast.  Light body, with a bit too much carbonation.  The flavor is similar to the aroma, with more opportunities to pick out the different aspects.  There is a citrus tang to it.  Not very sweet.  Orange, alcohol, cinnamon, coriander...  the whole gang is here.  The hops are very subdued, but extremely well balanced.

Pours hazy gold, with a fluffy head that wont quit.  lots of lacing as well.  Aroma is yeasty and spicy.  The flavors are peppery with alcohol being more dominant in the flavor than any beer I can remember off the top of my head.

Pours hazy orange with a thick two finger orange/tan head.  Aroma is fruity, mostly baked apple smells in this one for me.  Flavors are vaguely fruity, with yeasty notes coming through.  Lively carbonation, with a bitter finish.

Had high hopes of finding a Pumpkin beer that wasnt thin and bland tasting.  This one isnt much better than the low end pumpkin beers.  I was hoping for a bit of a sweeter/stronger brew to help balance out the spices that are very present in this beer.  Not a winner from dogfish head.

Pours deep copper color with a soft fluffy head.  Aroma isnt much to speak of, some malt, musty hops.  Flavor is sweet, and I think is the best part of the beer.  Not that its all that complex or mind blowing, but it has about the right sweetness for a german-style beer, and the hops linger on the back end.  Malt is definitely the biggest player in this one.

Interesting beer...  pours bright orange under a thick white head.  Aroma is yeasty and sweet.  Flavor is a bit too sweet, very much like a sweet white wine.  There is a vinous quality to it throughout.

Pours hazy orange under a thin white head.  Aroma is yeasty and sweet, with alcohol present.  Flavors are sweet on the front, with moderate alcohol, finish is slightly bitter, with herbal notes.  Some woody notes from the subdued hops, but mostly the yeast takes center stage, bringing out the flavors of this malty beer.  Mouthfeel is thicker than expected, with just about the right amount of carbonation (Unibroue sometimes seems over carbonated to me).
Pours a light amber with a dissipating head.  Aroma is a bit too "green" to me.  Flavor is malty, with some hops on the end.  Not one of my favorite lagers.

Pours black with a rocky brown head.  Aroma is roasted malts with some hint of funkiness that its hard to put your finger on (maybe the green olives that someone mentioned)---  flavor is a bit salty, like the aforementioned olives.  A little too sweet with not as much going on as I would like.  The hoppiness of this one is nice, but seems a bit out of place for some reason...  hard to describe, but I think this beer just misses it for some reason.

Hops... if ratebeer would allow one word reviews, that would be it.  Aroma is sticky with hops, flavor is sticky with hops- predominate high alpha for bitterness and cascade for grapefruit bitterness.  As a hophead, Im not sure you could do better.  For what it is, it is almost perfect.  Hopslam or 90 minute do a better job at making a balanced beer, but this one sets out to deliver hops, and succeeds..

2007 bottle.  Im developing more of a taste for the imperials--- especially when they are done well, as this one is.  Aroma carries the roasted goodness of a stout immediately...  Pours jet black with a frothy brown head.  I might have to chisel the lacing off of the glass.  Flavors are burnt, chocolaty malts, with a nicely balanced soy sauce note.  The hops hold up in this one as well.  I think that Cascade isnt usually a hop thats used in Imp Stout, and it gives this one a different character than most.  The swallow is sweet, but the hops dry out the palate.

Hazy brown with a lacy head.  Good lacing.  Sweet aroma, with a vegetal note with the yeast expected from Unibroue.  Flavor is sweet and rich, with herbal, spice, and caramel flavors.  Definite alcohol bite to this one.  Some soy sauce flavors that usually are present in imperial stouts...  very interesting beer...  maybe not as easily drinkable as the 16, but much more complex.

Pours a nice amber/brown with a frothy tan head.  Aroma is sweetish with predominant yeast.  Flavors are a bit fruity, but not as sweet as expected.  Weakest point of this beer is that it is a bit thin, and somewhat overcarbonated.   Good beer.
Not a bad beer... but just middling in every aspect.  It is a bit thin, there is some hop character, but nothing mindblowing.  Got this one in a mix pack...  probably the only time Ill have it...

Pours a clear burnt orange, with a rocky tan head.  Aroma smells stronger of hops than most lagers, and the flavor matches it.  This beer has much more going for it than I thought.  The crisp malt on the back end of this is about all I can pick out that I would qualify as a lager.  The flavor is rich and hoppy.  The presence of the hops almost push this into more of a pale ale flavor profile.

Pours a murky yellow... not the best look in a beer.  the head is nicely formed, but then goes away quickly.  aroma is spicy and sweet... you can really get the honey in the aroma.  Also a fair amount of mint aroma.  Flavor is peppery with a sweetness that is fairly well balanced.  There is some mint to the flavor as well.  Nice beer...  very different than most anything else out there.

Wow...  pours a dark brown with hints of red... thick tan head.  Aroma is similar to other Unibroue beers... yeasty, with the dark fruits you would expect.  the flavor is so much better in this one than others from the brewery though.  The strong alcohol and the sweetness keep fighting with each other...  dark fruit flavors, raisins, dates, quite a bit of malt as well.  The finish is dry with a tingle of alcohol.  Im a fan of this one.

Pours cloudy amber with a thin head.  The aroma is the real winner of this one.  Yeasty, musty, fruity, and spicy.  Mouthfeel is a bit thin, and the carbonation is heavy.  There is an alcohol bite to this one as well...  10% and you can tell it.  The flavor is dry, with just a bit of sweetness.  A lot of the aroma blends in with the flavor- so you can duplicate my notes from that... could be because the aroma is so strong on this one.  I think this would have been a lot higher rating if not for the overbearing carbonation...

beer_brewer_name: Schneider Weisse G. Schneider & Sohn GmbH
review_blob: Pours hazy brown/red with a dense white head.  Aroma is pure phenols...  lots of banana, christmas spices, and sweetness.  Flavors follow suit.  Strong banana flavor, with a huge clove kick as the beer warms.  Obviously a strong beer by the flavors, etc, but the alcohol is hidden.  No burn or flavor from the alcohol.  A true testament to what can be done just by fermentation.  Amazing that yeast can produce this many flavors.

Pours a glowing hazy orange.  Thin white head.  Sticky hop aroma.  Citrus flavors up front, followed by woodsy floral hops on the back end.  Not as sweet as the aroma had me think it would be.  Definitely brewed to be a vessel for hops, the malt isnt that strong.  I was expecting this great divide beer to push the Pale Ale a bit more to the IPA class, but they reel it in a bit and come off with a nicely balanced american pale.  Very true to the style.
beer_name: Great Divide Fresh Hop Pale Ale

review_blob: Not my thing, thats for sure.  Rating this based on what I think it would rate against others of its kind.  Tastes like a fruitless lambic.  Which I guess is about right.  I thought this would be a woody, earthy beer.  But instead it is a vinegary thin form of guerze, etc...  Whereas geurze tastes earthy and interesting, this one is just too sour.  Could be a bad bubbly white wine...

Draft...  black beer, frothy tan head...didnt stick around long.  Aroma is of a variety of roasted grains with a hint of hops.  More than you get from most of the malt bomb stouts.  Flavors of coffee, dark chocolate, earthiness...  the hops add an interesting note to this one.  Great stout.

Pours black with a frothy brown head.  Nice lacing.   Aroma is nice, but a bit one dimensional...  Flavors of coffee and chocolate dominate the flavors.  Heavy roasted malts are the key here... lots of black malt kick that gives it the roasted, so bitter its sweet type of feel to it.  The only real strike against this one is that its considerably thinner than most oatmeal stouts.

(22oz bottle)  Pours a cloudy straw color, with a bright white fluffy cream soda head.  Aroma is heavy on the banana, but there is a funky undertone that Im not a fan of.  Body is thin, but you cant critique a wit too much for that.  There are some nice flavors to this one.  Banana of course, but the spices come through a bit more in the flavor than the aroma to me.  From the bottle, I like this the best of the New Belgium brews Ive had.

Pours a hazy gold...  not much head.  Does not look or smell like a wheat beer to me.  Maybe Im not as familiar with american wheat as I need to be.  Aroma is of wet grains, and the flavor is moderately hopped watered down wheat beer.  Not necessarily a bad beer, but just nothing special.  Too watery with too little going on with it.

Pours dark brown, with minimal head.  Aroma is roasty but minimal.  Nothing overwhelming.  Palate is a bit thinner than expected, and a little too fizzy on the swallow.  Flavors of malt and caramel, with just a bit of chocolate.  Not as up front with it as some chocolate stouts.  There is also a metallic taste to it, which isnt common to me with stouts.  Overall a good beer, but not a stout to get excited about.

Pours reddish black with a fluffy tan head.  Aroma is similar to flat tire, with a heavy roasted quality.  More akin to a smoked quality than roasted now that I think about it.  Flavor is a strong roasted barley.  There is the funky yeast undertone that Fat Tire has as well, somewhat of a sour note to it.  As a traditional ale, you can expect some different flavors in this one that might not keep a brewery in business these days, so I can appreciate it from that direction, but the beer itself leaves a bit to be desired.  Not very refined.

I was worried about this one...  with stones flair for the overdramatic in their hops, I was afraid that they would go overboard with the smoke in this one.  Not true at all.  I really dont get much smoke in this one at all.  It is a great porter though.  Pours opaque brown with a thin head.  Aroma is a bit smoky, with lots of chocolate malts in it.  Flavor is of a rich porter.  There is a bit more hops in this one (as expected from stone) which is a welcome addition.  Stone really doesnt seem to do bad beer.  As you drink this one, you get more of a woody smoke towards the middle to end of your drink.

A bit average in every way to me now.  This used to be my favorite "premium" beer, but now it seems watery and skunky.  I should expect the skunk from the clear bottle.  On a Corona or Kalik, the skunk can be a positive, but here it seems like it is just a way to ruin what could be a decent brown ale.  Reduce the skunk, and beef up the malt for a better mouthfeel and body, and it could be higher than this.  Just not enough here to get excited about.
